CDATA[@friendly_url@/guest/downloads/samples]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-ITEMS-LIST', 'BASIC-ITEMS-LIST', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'HOME-SHOWCASE-FLASH', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Home Showcase Falsh', '<DIV>\n<DIV>\n<TABLE>\n<TBODY>\n<TR>\n<TD>\n<OBJECT height=240 width=100><embed src=\"@portal_ctx@/html/themes/brochure/images/flash/showcase.swf\" height=\"100\" width=\"240\"></OBJECT></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV>\n<DIV><BR><FONT size=2>Liferay Portal is being used globally across industries to meet the need for reliable, cost-effective, and innovative internet-based applications and infrastructure. </FONT></DIV>\n<DIV><FONT size=2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>\n<DIV>\n<DIV><FONT size=2>Companies routinely choose Liferay Portal for&nbsp;its out-of-the-box functionality, compatibility across all major application servers and database platforms, scalability, and the relentless innovation of its development team.</FONT></DIV>\n<DIV><FONT size=2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV><FONT size=2><A href=\"/web/guest/stories\"><FONT size=2>Read more</FONT></A> on how select companies are using Liferay for their most challenging information technology needs</FONT><FONT size=2>. </FONT></DIV></DIV>', 'general', '', '', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-EWEEK', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Liferay Brings Desktop Capabilities to the Web', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.eweek.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.eweek.com/article2/0,1759,1879782,00.asp]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[eWeek writer Jim Rapoza declares: \"With one of the richest and most desktoplike browser-based interfaces that we\'ve seen in commercial or open-source software, Liferay Portal 3.6.1 clearly impresses at first glance. The rest of the open-source product\'s capabilities, although not as remarkable as the interface, are solid. Liferay is a flexible and highly customizable solution for portals or Web sites.\"]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-FEED', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'News RSS Feed', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"feed-title\" type=\"text\">\n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[Liferay News and Anouncements]]></dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"feed-description\" type=\"text_box\">\n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[This is an RSS feed of highlighted news articles and anouncements about Liferay LLC and its flagship product Liferay Portal.]]></dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-FEED', 'BASIC-RSS-FEED', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-GOODWILL', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Goodwill.org launches its new website on top of Liferay Portal!', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.goodwill.org]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&amp;STORY=/www/story/11-08-2005/0004211036]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[Goodwill announced today that Liferay Portal is the key software driving MyGoodwill, a new organizational Intranet site for employees and volunteers of Goodwill Industries International.  MyGoodwill, which began operation this week, is a landmark organizational tool for the international nonprofit, enabling thousands of Goodwill staff worldwide to collaborate, share best practices and engage in real-time learning.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-IT-ANALYSIS', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Liferay after Plumtree', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.it-analysis.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.it-analysis.com/article.php?articleid=12945]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[The acquisition of Plumtree by BEA is being touted as as representing the end of the pure portal play vendor. However, Liferay is singled out as one of the few remaining pure portal vendors in the market.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-LEP361', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Liferay Portal 3.6.1 is released', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.liferay.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&amp;STORY=/www/story/09-13-2005/0004106422]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[Liferay Portal 3.6.1 is out! New features include drag and drop portlets, Spring based transactions and remoting, and hot deployable custom layouts. \n]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-LEP400RC1', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Liferay Portal 4.0.0 RC1 is released!', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.liferay.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.liferay.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[The much anticipated Liferay Portal 4.0.0 RC1 is released!!  Fine-grained security model, enterprise taxonomy, delegated and cascading permissions and administration, public and private pages, JSR-170 compliance via Jackrabbit integration, and page-level themes to the popular open-source portal application.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-LINE56', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Evaluating Open Source Enterprise Portal Software', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.line56.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.line56.com/articles/default.asp?articleID=7045]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[Web portal options are in the plenty and free open source products are tempting. But are they any good? Read about what James McGovern, an architect of a Fortune 100 company, has to say about Liferay Portal.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-LINE56-2', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'A Free Portal', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.line56.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.line56.com/articles/default.asp?articleID=7492]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[Line56 investigates the free, open source Liferay.  It is both flexible and backed by options like services and training.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-LINUXWORLD', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Open Source Portal Software Controls Security', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.linuxworld.com.au]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.linuxworld.com.au/index.php/id;1997719577;fp;4;fpid;3]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[With the help of Goodwill Industries International, Liferay Portal 4.0 lets individual users, groups and guests have portlet-level permissions. Administrators can set or restrict access to portlets and portlet objects, as well as delegate access authority to others.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-MICROSOFT-PRICES', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Microsoft\'s high prices drive FSW to Linux, open source', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[searchopensource.techtarget.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://searchopensource.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid39_gci1176366,00.html]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[High costs and an urgent need for standards compliance is driving FSW Inc. away from Microsoft and into new worlds, such as server virtualization on Linux, an open source and Linux backend and open source desktops.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-NETWORKWORLD', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Open source: corporate playground?', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.networkworld.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.networkworld.com/newsletters/datacenter/2005/1017datacenter1.html]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[The world of open source allows coporations to take advantage of free software and harness the flexibility of addressing individual needs. With Liferay as his model, Andreas Antonopoulos writes: \"The open source community that emerges around such projects is a focal point for collaboration between companies pursuing similar goals.\" Each company, then, reaps the benefits of features and enhancements done by another.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-TECHTARGET', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Open source portal lets Goodwill CIO help those in need', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[searchopensource.techtarget.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://searchopensource.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid39_gci1135884,00.html]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[\"You\'re seeing in the news every day that the Suns and IBMs are moving toward this world as well. I was able to look to the Liferay client list that Brian [Chan] had put together and could see the tens of thousands using it. Seeing news like that makes you feel pretty confident in open source,\" said Stephen Bergman, CIO of Goodwill Industries.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-TSS', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Kito Mann to present JSF on top of Liferay at TheServerSide Symposium', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.theserverside.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://javasymposium.techtarget.com/html/det_descriptions.htm#KMannJSF]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[Component-oriented user interface frameworks such as JavaServer Faces (JSF) are growing in popularity, and organizations are also beginning to recognize the power of building application components with the Portlet API. What many don\'t realize, however, is the fact that JSF has integrated support for the Portlet API, making it a natural fit for building portlets. This session starts with a brief overview of JSF, portlets, and portals. It then explains how JSF portlet support works, and examines the process of developing portlets with JSF. Next, it walks through the development of a simple JSF application and deployment of that application as a portlet inside of Liferay Enterprise Portal, an open-source portal server.\n]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'NEWS-RSS-WALDEN', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'The Lion, the Witch, and Linux', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"creator\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.newsforge.com]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"link\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://software.newsforge.com/software/06/02/27/1622243.shtml?tid=132]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"description\" type=\"text_box\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[Walden Media, the company that produced The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, The Witch and the Wardrobe, wanted a community-driven Web site that would encourage discussion and collaboration on the educational products related to its movies. After considering the options, Walden Media chose Liferay\'s MIT-licensed open source content management system (CMS), running on Linux.]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', 'BASIC-RSS-ITEM', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products', '<DIV>\n<DIV>\n<DIV>\n<DIV><STRONG>Open Source&nbsp;Innovation -- Enterprise Reliability</STRONG><BR></DIV>\n<DIV>At Liferay we believe that a passionate development team working in open&nbsp;collaboration will produce a product that rivals the best of commercial offerings. The open source model empowers our team to bring robust,&nbsp;innovative, and flexible&nbsp;products to market more quickly and at lower cost than traditional development models. In addition, subjecting the source to the scrutiny of its users ensures our product&nbsp;reliability&nbsp;meets the highest standards.</DIV>\n<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>\n<UL>\n<LI><SPAN style=\"FONT-WEIGHT: bold\"><A href=\"/web/guest/products/portal\">Liferay Portal</A></SPAN> is our flagship product.&nbsp;Now in its sixth year of development, Liferay Portal is JSR-168 compliant and runs on almost any major application server, database, and operating system, rendering over 700 <A href=\"/web/guest/products/portal/deployment_matrix\">deployment</A>&nbsp;combinations.&nbsp;<BR><BR>With over 50 portlets prebundled and more than 20 community-contributed themes&nbsp;available, Liferay Portal is unsurpassed in out-of-the-box functionality, bringing immediate usability and accelerated development potential to a broad swath of portal-based internet application scenarios.<BR><BR></LI>\n<LI><SPAN style=\"FONT-WEIGHT: bold\"><A href=\"/web/guest/products/journal\">Liferay Journal</A> </SPAN>is a built-in content management system (CMS) leveraging the technologies of Liferay Portal.&nbsp; Separation of content from layout and roles-based permissioning and workflow help your organization maintain editorial rights and integrity, allow for content versioning, and increase productivity, empowering writers and designers to focus on their respective areas. A good content management system can significantly reduce the operating cost of publishing, managing,&nbsp;and maintaining web content and document libraries. <BR><BR></LI>\n<LI><SPAN style=\"FONT-WEIGHT: bold\"><A href=\"/web/guest/products/mesh\">Liferay Mesh</A></SPAN> is an upcoming technology from Liferay. Watch this space for more information soon.<BR></LI></UL></DIV></DIV></DIV>', 'general', '', '', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-CMS-DOCUMENT-LIBRARY', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products CMS Document Library', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"image\" type=\"image\">\n    <dynamic-content id=\"liferay.com.journal.article.PRODUCTS-CMS-DOCUMENT-LIBRARY.image.1.0\">/image/journal/article?img_id=PRODUCTS-CMS-DOCUMENT-LIBRARY.image&amp;version=1.0</dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"textarea\" type=\"text_area\">\n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[<DIV>\n<DIV><STRONG>Document Library</STRONG></DIV><BR>The Document Library provides a centralized repository for various documents (e.g., .PDF, .DOC, .XLS, etc.) to be stored and given a unique URL.&nbsp; A company\'s intranet running Liferay Portal&nbsp;can then be able to post internal documentation used for employees.&nbsp; Alternatively, since each document has its own URL, a portlet on your company\'s public website can reference any of the documents stored there as well.</DIV>]]></dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-IMAGE-TEXT', 'BASIC-IMAGETEXT', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-CMS-IMAGE-GALLERY', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products CMS Image Gallery', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"image\" type=\"image\">\n    <dynamic-content id=\"liferay.com.journal.article.PRODUCTS-CMS-IMAGE-GALLERY.image.1.0\">/image/journal/article?img_id=PRODUCTS-CMS-IMAGE-GALLERY.image&amp;version=1.0</dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"textarea\" type=\"text_area\">\n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[<DIV>\n<DIV><STRONG>Image Gallery</STRONG></DIV>\n<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>\n<DIV>Like the Document Library, the Image Gallery provides a central repository for images used throughout the Liferay Portal by a unique URL.&nbsp; A company can add images, reference them in the portal, and view all your images through&nbsp;a slideshow.</DIV></DIV>]]></dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-IMAGE-TEXT', 'BASIC-IMAGETEXT', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-CMS-STRUCTURED-CONTENT', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products CMS Structured Content', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"image\" type=\"image\"> \n    <dynamic-content id=\"liferay.com.journal.article.PRODUCTS-CMS-STRUCTURED-CONTENT.image.1.0\">/image/journal/article?img_id=PRODUCTS-CMS-STRUCTURED-CONTENT.image&amp;version=1.0</dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"textarea\" type=\"text_area\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[<DIV><STRONG>Structured Content</STRONG></DIV>\n<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>\n<DIV>Liferay Journal segregates the creation of content between designer and writer.&nbsp; Less technical persons can create web content using one of the built-in WYSIWGs (What You See Is What You Get editors) without sifting through complex code.&nbsp; Assign a web designer to layout the data without having to come up with content.&nbsp; Liferay Journal divides the process into three different areas: structures, templates, and articles.</DIV>]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-IMAGE-TEXT', 'BASIC-IMAGETEXT', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-CMS-SUPPORTED-JSR170', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products CMS Supported JSR-170', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"image\" type=\"image\">\n    <dynamic-content id=\"liferay.com.journal.article.PRODUCTS-CMS-SUPPORTED-JSR170.image.1.0\">/image/journal/article?img_id=PRODUCTS-CMS-SUPPORTED-JSR170.image&amp;version=1.0</dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"textarea\" type=\"text_area\">\n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[<DIV><STRONG>JSR-170</STRONG></DIV>\n<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>\n<DIV>Developed under the Java Community Process (JCP), JSR-170 is a Content Repository API for CMS.&nbsp; The Document Library is currently compliant.&nbsp; More portlets will be migrated over in future releases.&nbsp; This will provide 100% JSR-170 and backwards compatibility.</DIV>]]></dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-IMAGE-TEXT', 'BASIC-IMAGETEXT-WRAP', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-CMS-SUPPORTED-OTHER', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products CMS Supported Other', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root> \n  <dynamic-element name=\"image\" type=\"image\"> \n    <dynamic-content id=\"liferay.com.journal.article.PRODUCTS-CMS-SUPPORTED-OTHER.image.1.0\">/image/journal/article?img_id=PRODUCTS-CMS-SUPPORTED-OTHER.image&amp;version=1.0</dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"textarea\" type=\"text_area\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[<DIV>\n<DIV><STRONG>Other Supported Technologies</STRONG></DIV>\n<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>\n<DIV>Just as Liferay runs on most application servers and databases, we strive to be content-agnostic as well.&nbsp; This means, with Liferay, you have the freedom to integrate with your favorite content repository -- whether it be the Liferay Journal, another open-source alternative like <A href=\"http://www.alfresco.com/\">Alfresco</A> and <A href=\"http://www.magnolia.info/en/magnolia.html\">Magnolia</A>, or a closed-source vendor like <A href=\"http://www.vignette.com/\">Vignette</A>.</DIV></DIV>]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element> \n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-IMAGE-TEXT', 'BASIC-TEXTIMAGE-WRAP', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-CMS-XSL-EDITOR', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products CMS XSL Editor', '<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n\n<root>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"image\" type=\"image\">\n    <dynamic-content id=\"liferay.com.journal.article.PRODUCTS-CMS-XSL-EDITOR.image.1.0\">/image/journal/article?img_id=PRODUCTS-CMS-XSL-EDITOR.image&amp;version=1.0</dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n  <dynamic-element name=\"textarea\" type=\"text_area\">\n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[<DIV><STRONG>Flexible Templating Mechanism (XSL/VM)</STRONG> \n<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>Templates used for creating articles can be created in either XSL or Velocity (VM), giving developers flexibility in designing their websites.</DIV>]]></dynamic-content>\n  </dynamic-element>\n</root>', 'general', 'BASIC-IMAGE-TEXT', 'BASIC-IMAGETEXT', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-LICENSING', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products Licensing', '<div>Liferay Portal is an open source portal that helps organizations collaborate more efficiently by providing a consolidated view of disparate applications. It is used by large and small organizations all over the world. Liferay has an extensive list of features that compares with most commercial portals but without the high license fees.<br><br><b>Business Friendly&nbsp;Open Source License</b><br><br>Liferay is made available under the <a href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/mit-license.php\">MIT license</a>, which is essentially the same as the Apache and BSD licenses. Unlike the GPL or LGPL licenses, the MIT/Apache/BSD licenses&nbsp;are business friendly and contain no license fees or reciprocity clauses. This means you can bundle Liferay or your branch of Liferay and even resell it if you want. There are no strings attached.<br><br>Companies benefit when they choose to contribute their bug fixes and modifications back to Liferay because they can more easily upgrade to the latest version of Liferay without paying the penalty of spending time and energy reintegrating their own custom changes. Our large community of contributors can even improve on another company\'s contributions - creating a steam roll effect of quality open source software.<br><br>Companies also benefit when they can build value on top of Liferay and choose not to contribute it so they can resell their modifications. We don\'t believe that just because we give our product you have to also. We believe a business friendly open source license gives companies greater protection in their investment by providing more options.<br><br><b>Liferay vs. Closed Source Portals</b><br><br>Liferay provides the lowest total cost of ownership. There are ZERO license fees. Don\'t pay more because you add more users or need to scale with more CPUs and servers.<br><br>Liferay has no application server agenda. Don\'t be forced into buying more licenses because your portal was made by the same vendor that made your application server. Mix and match so you get the best of breed.<br><br>You can develop portlets with a full featured IDE like Eclipse, Netbeans, and JBuilder or with lightweight editor like EditPlus, VI, and Emacs. Commercial portals love to sell tools that <a href=\"http://www.theserverside.com/news/thread.tss?thread_id=31302#153713\">promise</a> to save you time and money but almost always end up wasting you time and money. This isn\'t 1999. Save money.<br><br>Open source means the code is in your hands. If you want to customize it, you <i>can</i>. If there are security flaws, everyone is made aware and the community can participate in fixing it quickly. There is actually <i>less</i> risk in going with a sustained open source product than in going with a commercial vendor. Vendors can go out of business. Vendors can merge and render your product dead in the water. Sustained open source products have an active community around it that works together.<br><br><b>Liferay vs. Open Source Portals</b><br><br>Not all open source licenses are created equal. Some licenses require that your modifications be contributed if you choose to sell or distribute your product. Some open source vendors still charge a license fee for commercial use. Others are confused and flip flop from being closed source one minute and open source the next minute. Liferay is open source because we believe it is the next step in the evolution of software development.<br><br>Liferay has a very active community as evidenced by our active <a href=\"http://forums.liferay.com/\">forums</a>. If you\'re a small organization that doesn\'t require mission critical response times, you\'ll get the help you need. If your organization requires mission critical support so that your project deadlines are not compromised, you can get direct access to the developers of Liferay through professional support and consulting. Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:sales@liferay.com\">sales@liferay.com</a> for more information about our services.</div>', 'general', '', '', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, TRUE, 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE);
insert into JournalArticle (companyId, articleId, version, groupId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, title, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired) values ('liferay.com', 'PRODUCTS-LIFERAYPORTAL-DEPLOYMENTMATRIX', 1.0, '2', 'liferay.com.1', 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'Products Liferay Portal Deployment Matrix', '<DIV>\n<DIV>\n<DIV>Liferay Portal wants to make the <B><I>J2EE</I></B> promise of write once run anywhere a reality so you can reuse your existing resources and deploy the portal the way you want to when you want to. Reuse what you have or use what\'s free so you can stick with your budget and get an immediate return on investment that everyone can be happy with.<BR><BR>There are <B>700</B> ways you can deploy the portal, with more ways to come as we add support for Geronimo, GlassFish, and JFox. Is there another application server or database you use that is not in this list? Contact us at <A href=\"mailto:staff@liferay.com\">staff@liferay.com</A> and we\'ll add support for it as soon as possible.</DIV>\n<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>\n<DIV>\n<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>\n<TBODY>\n<TR>\n<TD class=content vAlign=top>\n<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>\n<TBODY>\n<TR>\n<TD class=content>\n<FIELDSET><LEGEND><B>Application Servers</B></LEGEND>\n<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=8 border=0>\n<TBODY>\n<TR>\n<TD class=content>\n<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>\n<TBODY>\n<TR>\n<TD class=content><B>BES</B></TD>\n<TD class=content>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>\n<TD class=content>Borland ES 6.5 </TD></TR>\n<TR>\n<TD class=content><B>GER</B></TD>\n<TD class=content>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>\n<TD class=content>Geronimo</TD></TR>\n<TR>\n<TD class=content><B>GLF</B></TD>\n<TD class=content>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>\n<TD class=content>GlassFish</TD></TR>\n<TR>\n<TD class=content><B>JB</B></TD>\n<TD class=content>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>\n<TD class=content