and its new intranet site. Known as MyGoodwill, this new site was to create a landmark organizational tool for the international nonprofit company, enabling thousands of Goodwill staff worldwide to collaborate, share best practices, and engage in real-time learning. Additionally, at Goodwill, as with other nonprofits, staying within budget is always a major concern. A solution that provided the most powerful and flexible technologies at the lowest cost was a high priority. <BR><BR><B>Resolution</B> <BR><BR>When Goodwill first selected Liferay, their IT team had many reservations about going with an open source product. As progress continued, Goodwill\'s fears quickly dissipated. Bergman said, \"First and foremost is an accelerated return on investment, which allows us to make additional site features possible sooner. Liferay Portal is easily adaptable to Goodwill\'s data center architecture and the diverse combination of technologies that we employ. Finally, it offers exceptional robustness and scalability. Liferay Portal was by far the most cost effective and efficient portal technology we considered.\" Liferay implemented the following: \n<UL>\n<LI>Collaborative chat and message board capabilities</LI>\n<LI>Distribution of knowledge via Blogs</LI>\n<LI>\"Wiki\" pages that were regularly updated by visitors</LI>\n<LI>Interface to Computer-Based Training modules</LI>\n<LI>Document repository</LI></UL>Liferay easily exceeded all of Goodwill\'s expectations. Customizations that Bergman expected to be done in six to eight weeks were done over one weekend. Not only did it provide all the desired functionality, it also provided an unexpected, long-term cost savings. All fears were relieved when the Liferay implementations were completed. </DIV>]]></dynamic-content> \n  </dynamic-element>  \n  <dynamic-element name=\"screenshot-thumbnail-1\" type=\"text\"> \n    <dynamic-content><![CDATA[content.liferay.com/4.0.0/images/COMPANY-CASE-STUDIES-GOODWILL.screenshot-thumbnail-1